I am executor-designate for my mother's estate.  In (preliminary)
discussions among the beneficiaries, there are some who want one brother
to get certain things that the will does not appear to call for.  Eg:
the will says only that he should get certain &quot;real property&quot;; they want
him to also get the contents of that property.  Again, the will says
that the remaining assets should be divided equally; they want him to
also get the car.

I'm not thrilled with this, but I'm willing to accept it.  It's not a
large portion of the total estate, and there's enough bitterness
already.  However, I do wonder just how far we can deviate from the
language of the will.  Are there any rules of thumb?

If we do it this way, and everyone signs something saying that they know
what they're doing, would that protect me from future liability?

(We do have an attorney, but I'm a little unsure how much to trust her:
it seems like either what the will says is just what my mother intended,
or the attorney didn't address what seem like very basic questions.)

TIA,
George
</POST>
