George,

The heirs to your mother's will want to divide the estate differently
from the way she specified in her will. You are the executor, and you
wonder how far to go in &quot;deviating&quot; from the language.

I'm not a lawyer, but my answer is: not by a hairsbreadth. If people
are all agreed now but later are unhappy or change their minds, any
deviation will come back to bite you in the ass.

Fortunately, you can keep everyone happy *and* keep yourself legally
in the clear. Simply distribute everything according to the terms of
the will, and let the heirs make gifts to each other as they choose.
They can do this without involving you in any way, just as any adult
can give personal property to any other adult. If they are truly all
in agreement as you say, this will be quite routine, and there should
be no tax consequences unless the gifts are much larger than you
imply.

