As usual, the authoritative answer is  &quot;insufficient detail&quot;.  &lt;wry grin&gt;

*IF* the language of the will consists of two sections;
1) a list of 'specific bequests',
2) directions as the division of the 'unspecified' property.

Things specified in the first section _must_ be distributed as specified,
unlesss the beneficiary has predeceased the testator.

That which is covered by the second section is a somewhat more complex
issue.  Since nothing is specifically named, nor has an explicitly
assigned value -- there is no easy way determine, other than by 'selling
on the open market' (generally construed to be 'at auction'), all those items,
and dividing  the proceeds of that sale as specified.

However, *IF* _all_ the beneficiaries under that second section of the
will execute documents agreeing to a particular valuation assigned to
specific assets of the estate, then those ojects _themselves_ can be
distributed to beneficiaries as part of their 'share' of the 'proceeds'
of the estate.

Note: such a 'mutually agreed' valuation can be above or _below_ the 'fair
market value' of the item.  As long as _everybody_ with a possible 'interest'
in  the item signs off on the value, that *is* the value for estate
distribution purposes.

If _everbody_ involved wants to go this route, your attorney should be
ablde to trivially produce the appropriate paperwork.
